WEBVTT

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:02.000
All right, good afternoon, everybody.

00:00:02.000 --> 00:00:05.600
Hope everybody enjoyed Atlanta's King of Pops.

00:00:05.600 --> 00:00:06.840
It's a very large stateful here,

00:00:06.840 --> 00:00:08.800
so I'm really glad those of you who are out of town

00:00:08.800 --> 00:00:10.160
got to enjoy it.

00:00:10.160 --> 00:00:11.440
My name is Julianne Gent,

00:00:11.440 --> 00:00:13.720
and today I'm gonna be talking about some ways

00:00:13.720 --> 00:00:15.280
that we are protecting

00:00:15.280 --> 00:00:17.639
some of our frontline healthcare heroes

00:00:17.639 --> 00:00:19.400
in regards to specifically billing.

00:00:20.400 --> 00:00:22.480
So imagine, if you will, with me.

00:00:22.480 --> 00:00:24.280
You are an intensive care physician.

00:00:24.280 --> 00:00:26.799
You see and take care of the sickest patients

00:00:26.799 --> 00:00:28.200
in the hospital.

00:00:28.200 --> 00:00:32.119
You are at the end of the third consecutive 12-hour shift,

00:00:32.119 --> 00:00:33.880
and half of the people in your unit

00:00:33.880 --> 00:00:37.680
needed some sort of life-saving treatment just today.

00:00:37.680 --> 00:00:39.119
You then suddenly get a call

00:00:39.119 --> 00:00:41.520
from your hospital's billing department,

00:00:41.520 --> 00:00:43.720
and the manager says that they received a complaint

00:00:43.720 --> 00:00:45.880
from one of your previous patients

00:00:45.880 --> 00:00:49.160
saying that their insurance is denying your care

00:00:49.160 --> 00:00:50.000
and that they must pay

00:00:50.000 --> 00:00:53.459
for their entire hospital visit out of pocket.

00:00:53.459 --> 00:00:57.020
Then, on cue, you get a call from your director's office

00:00:57.020 --> 00:00:59.380
where an auditor from the Center for Medicaid

00:00:59.380 --> 00:01:02.279
and Medicare Services is sitting.

00:01:02.279 --> 00:01:03.820
They inform you that they've reviewed

00:01:03.820 --> 00:01:05.660
several of your clinical notes

00:01:05.660 --> 00:01:09.419
and are accusing you of medical fraud.

00:01:10.459 --> 00:01:12.500
They actually show you the note in question

00:01:12.500 --> 00:01:14.440
which is related to the same patient

00:01:14.440 --> 00:01:16.699
who had called billing earlier.

00:01:16.699 --> 00:01:18.099
Here's the note here,

00:01:18.099 --> 00:01:21.220
and all of this happened simply because

00:01:21.220 --> 00:01:23.940
you added an extra zero on accident

00:01:23.940 --> 00:01:25.779
in your long documentation

00:01:25.779 --> 00:01:28.739
claiming that you were billing for 300 minutes

00:01:28.739 --> 00:01:29.739
instead of 30.

00:01:30.900 --> 00:01:35.180
So, this might seem like a very exaggerated situation,

00:01:35.180 --> 00:01:37.900
but this can easily happen to our overworked

00:01:37.900 --> 00:01:40.059
and burned-out clinicians

00:01:40.059 --> 00:01:41.540
where these simple clerical errors

00:01:41.540 --> 00:01:45.639
could lose the patients, their jobs, and their reputation.

00:01:45.639 --> 00:01:48.419
So, seeing this happen at other healthcare entities

00:01:48.419 --> 00:01:52.339
and foreseeing that this may happen to us in the future,

00:01:52.339 --> 00:01:54.900
our executive leadership came to our team

00:01:54.900 --> 00:01:56.300
with the following question.

00:01:57.339 --> 00:01:59.500
Can we help clinicians maintain

00:01:59.500 --> 00:02:01.699
accurate billing documentation

00:02:01.699 --> 00:02:05.139
while meeting them where they're at?

00:02:05.139 --> 00:02:08.899
Basically, how can we help physicians do their job better

00:02:08.899 --> 00:02:13.300
without increasing their already overburdened workload?

00:02:14.199 --> 00:02:16.820
So, of course, our office said, of course we can.

00:02:16.820 --> 00:02:19.539
So, we actually considered a couple of solutions.

00:02:20.380 --> 00:02:23.339
The first was to require clinicians to review

00:02:23.339 --> 00:02:25.880
every single note they've written that day

00:02:25.880 --> 00:02:28.660
and double-check for billing accuracy.

00:02:28.660 --> 00:02:29.979
Well, we just talked about that we need

00:02:29.979 --> 00:02:31.559
to meet physicians where they're at.

00:02:31.559 --> 00:02:33.779
We're not gonna add yet another tedious task

00:02:33.779 --> 00:02:37.139
to their already long stack of tasks to do

00:02:37.139 --> 00:02:38.759
and take away from patient care.

00:02:39.979 --> 00:02:42.199
So, we're gonna go ahead and eliminate that.

00:02:42.199 --> 00:02:46.300
The second one we looked at was called a SMART phrase,

00:02:46.300 --> 00:02:48.800
and it is a functionality that is provided

00:02:48.800 --> 00:02:53.800
by our electronic medical record or EMR software vendor.

00:02:53.919 --> 00:02:55.320
So, basically what this does,

00:02:55.320 --> 00:02:58.279
it allows clinicians to type in the name of a template

00:02:58.279 --> 00:03:00.839
that consists of a lot of commonly used phrases.

00:03:00.839 --> 00:03:04.679
For example, here it says critical care billing statement.

00:03:04.679 --> 00:03:07.919
And then it automatically adds it to their note.

00:03:07.919 --> 00:03:10.600
So, the data typed into this phrase,

00:03:10.600 --> 00:03:12.360
where you can see with the three asterisks

00:03:12.360 --> 00:03:14.600
would be where you put the billing time,

00:03:14.600 --> 00:03:17.639
is actually stored very cleanly in a data warehouse

00:03:17.639 --> 00:03:19.460
where we can extract that data.

00:03:20.679 --> 00:03:24.399
However, we found two large issues with this approach.

00:03:24.399 --> 00:03:27.479
First, SMART phrase templates are just one

00:03:27.479 --> 00:03:31.160
of many documentation tools that physicians can use,

00:03:31.160 --> 00:03:33.839
that they're optional, they're not required,

00:03:33.839 --> 00:03:35.440
and many physicians don't use it.

00:03:35.440 --> 00:03:38.919
Many physicians like to write their own text in freehand.

00:03:38.919 --> 00:03:42.080
And secondly, we recently found that a lot

00:03:42.080 --> 00:03:45.960
of clinician workflow is doing the old copy and paste

00:03:45.960 --> 00:03:48.279
of notes from a previous,

00:03:48.279 --> 00:03:51.800
text from a previous note into a new note.

00:03:51.800 --> 00:03:53.919
This happens a lot when care is not changed

00:03:53.919 --> 00:03:55.279
from day to day with a patient

00:03:55.279 --> 00:03:57.979
and it saves them a lot of time and extra typing.

00:03:57.979 --> 00:04:01.160
But when this happens, the data that I showed

00:04:01.160 --> 00:04:04.679
in that asterisk in that phrase is no longer extractable.

00:04:04.679 --> 00:04:07.000
It is no longer put into that data warehouse.

00:04:08.800 --> 00:04:10.880
So, I know what a lot of data scientists

00:04:10.880 --> 00:04:12.960
in this room are probably thinking.

00:04:12.960 --> 00:04:16.359
This is just untextured, sorry, excuse me.

00:04:16.359 --> 00:04:18.679
This is unstructured text.

00:04:18.679 --> 00:04:20.320
Just use an LLM.

00:04:20.320 --> 00:04:22.399
We got asked this a lot by a lot of physicians.

00:04:22.399 --> 00:04:23.640
Can't you just use AI?

00:04:23.640 --> 00:04:25.519
What's this LLM?

00:04:25.519 --> 00:04:28.040
Well, we have a couple of limitations,

00:04:28.040 --> 00:04:30.079
especially, specifically to healthcare.

00:04:31.000 --> 00:04:33.480
So, there are three main challenges we face

00:04:33.480 --> 00:04:35.760
when we thought about using an LLM.

00:04:35.760 --> 00:04:36.959
The first being cost.

00:04:36.959 --> 00:04:39.440
We all know that LLMs are not cheap,

00:04:39.440 --> 00:04:42.160
but they also have a large infrastructure cost.

00:04:42.160 --> 00:04:44.959
So, if you're trying to run an LLM on a daily basis,

00:04:44.959 --> 00:04:49.000
requires powerful GPUs, a dedicated cloud space,

00:04:49.000 --> 00:04:51.239
which is something maybe a large university,

00:04:51.239 --> 00:04:53.799
a pharmaceutical company or tech company

00:04:53.799 --> 00:04:56.040
could have and support,

00:04:56.040 --> 00:04:59.399
but not a small to medium-ish healthcare system.

00:05:00.359 --> 00:05:01.200
Secondly,

00:05:04.279 --> 00:05:06.640
even if we somehow got the cost,

00:05:06.640 --> 00:05:08.760
both financially and infrastructurally,

00:05:08.760 --> 00:05:11.000
one of the issues is timeliness.

00:05:11.000 --> 00:05:13.119
Anything related to healthcare quality,

00:05:13.119 --> 00:05:15.200
so that means anything patient safety,

00:05:15.200 --> 00:05:16.880
or anything that could get audited

00:05:16.880 --> 00:05:20.640
by a government official or a regulatory branch,

00:05:20.640 --> 00:05:22.480
like as we saw earlier,

00:05:22.480 --> 00:05:24.399
the auditor coming for medical fraud,

00:05:24.399 --> 00:05:27.119
can come at any time, at any point of the year,

00:05:27.119 --> 00:05:28.679
and can come multiple times.

00:05:28.679 --> 00:05:30.359
So, we were given a turnaround time

00:05:30.359 --> 00:05:31.720
of about a week and a half.

00:05:31.720 --> 00:05:34.839
And there is not really a good feasible way in LLM

00:05:34.839 --> 00:05:39.559
we'd be able to train, validate in that timeframe

00:05:39.559 --> 00:05:41.760
to get ready for any potential auditing.

00:05:42.959 --> 00:05:46.359
And finally, the biggest one is HIPAA compliance.

00:05:46.359 --> 00:05:49.359
So, for those of you who are not from the U.S.,

00:05:49.359 --> 00:05:51.000
HIPAA is a federal law

00:05:51.000 --> 00:05:53.640
that protects patients' healthcare privacy and data

00:05:53.640 --> 00:05:56.119
that is taken very, very seriously.

00:05:56.119 --> 00:05:58.679
So, if we wanted to use an LLM

00:05:58.679 --> 00:06:02.720
that's already on market, like ChatGPT or Copilot,

00:06:02.720 --> 00:06:07.440
if we put healthcare data into that LLM,

00:06:07.440 --> 00:06:09.359
we would be violating HIPAA.

00:06:10.160 --> 00:06:11.239
And could have devastating consequences

00:06:11.239 --> 00:06:12.679
to a healthcare system.

00:06:12.679 --> 00:06:15.839
So, all in all, we scrapped the LLM.

00:06:15.839 --> 00:06:19.320
So, because we scrapped three of our main tools,

00:06:19.320 --> 00:06:22.559
we decided, why don't we just make our own?

00:06:22.559 --> 00:06:27.079
If you want it done right, do it yourself.

00:06:27.079 --> 00:06:29.000
So, how we built this tool.

00:06:29.000 --> 00:06:30.359
So, here's an example.

00:06:30.359 --> 00:06:33.679
Don't worry, healthcare people, this is fake data.

00:06:33.679 --> 00:06:35.359
We're not breaking HIPAA today.

00:06:35.359 --> 00:06:38.480
So, here's an example of what a typical

00:06:38.480 --> 00:06:41.720
hospital intensive care unit clinical note would look like.

00:06:41.720 --> 00:06:43.239
You can see it's all free text.

00:06:43.239 --> 00:06:44.359
It's incredibly messy.

00:06:44.359 --> 00:06:46.480
Tons of random numeric data.

00:06:47.480 --> 00:06:51.279
Luckily, our EMR vendor that I talked about earlier

00:06:51.279 --> 00:06:54.160
stores all of this free text in a data warehouse,

00:06:54.160 --> 00:06:57.160
which we can extract via SQL code.

00:06:57.160 --> 00:06:59.839
And we can also get a lot of other important information,

00:06:59.839 --> 00:07:02.440
like who wrote the note and when.

00:07:02.440 --> 00:07:05.160
And so, now we have this messy free text data

00:07:05.160 --> 00:07:06.200
in a cleaner format.

00:07:06.200 --> 00:07:08.320
So, we can now see Meredith Gray,

00:07:08.320 --> 00:07:11.399
our favorite dramatic physician,

00:07:11.399 --> 00:07:13.920
wrote this note for this patient on New Year's Day.

00:07:15.040 --> 00:07:18.640
So, we could theoretically take that SQL output,

00:07:18.640 --> 00:07:20.640
copy and paste it into an Excel file,

00:07:20.640 --> 00:07:22.200
and import it into R.

00:07:22.200 --> 00:07:23.079
But we're data people.

00:07:23.079 --> 00:07:24.600
We want things to be automated.

00:07:24.600 --> 00:07:28.079
We want to reduce the manual process as much as possible.

00:07:28.079 --> 00:07:31.799
So, instead, we utilized the ODBC package

00:07:31.799 --> 00:07:36.040
to connect the SQL data warehouse directly to R.

00:07:36.880 --> 00:07:40.239
And so, in the DB get query function down below,

00:07:40.239 --> 00:07:44.079
you can actually copy and paste your SQL query.

00:07:44.079 --> 00:07:47.760
And then, you can now directly import the data

00:07:47.760 --> 00:07:50.839
from the SQL data warehouse directly into R

00:07:50.839 --> 00:07:52.880
in one stop shop, one motion.

00:07:52.880 --> 00:07:55.079
No copy and pasting, no Excel needed.

00:07:56.640 --> 00:07:59.959
So, the next step was to create a data set of keywords

00:07:59.959 --> 00:08:01.079
that we find in these notes

00:08:01.079 --> 00:08:03.480
that are specifically related to billing.

00:08:03.480 --> 00:08:06.880
So, we actually worked with our critical care clinicians.

00:08:06.880 --> 00:08:09.200
They looked at several notes of their colleagues

00:08:09.200 --> 00:08:11.600
and kind of tagged the most commonly used phrases

00:08:11.600 --> 00:08:14.959
or the phrases that we would need to have in a note

00:08:14.959 --> 00:08:17.519
for regulatory purposes that are required.

00:08:17.519 --> 00:08:21.079
And we put these into a keyword data set.

00:08:21.079 --> 00:08:23.200
So, I'm showing probably about the first 15 or so,

00:08:23.200 --> 00:08:26.320
but there's tons because there's so much variation

00:08:26.320 --> 00:08:30.440
in ways that clinicians can bill and put that phrasing in.

00:08:30.440 --> 00:08:32.840
So, the reason we also include the minutes

00:08:32.840 --> 00:08:35.400
or min information is because when you saw

00:08:35.400 --> 00:08:37.679
in the free text note previously,

00:08:37.679 --> 00:08:39.059
there's lots of numeric values.

00:08:39.059 --> 00:08:41.919
There's telephone numbers, there's labs, there's vitals,

00:08:41.919 --> 00:08:45.440
there's PIC numbers, which is a physician number.

00:08:45.440 --> 00:08:47.559
And so, we wanna make sure that

00:08:47.559 --> 00:08:49.280
because we aren't using an LLM,

00:08:49.280 --> 00:08:52.119
we want the tool to be able to pull the number

00:08:52.119 --> 00:08:54.520
and know that the number is the number of minutes

00:08:54.520 --> 00:08:58.799
and not a blood pressure or a heart rate.

00:09:00.679 --> 00:09:02.760
And so, finally, we coded the function

00:09:03.640 --> 00:09:05.520
that serves as our NLP, and we were actually able

00:09:05.520 --> 00:09:08.679
to use this with some very basic and ready-to-use

00:09:08.679 --> 00:09:12.479
and readily available tools from Posit.

00:09:12.479 --> 00:09:14.140
Tidyverse, Dipler, and Stringer.

00:09:14.140 --> 00:09:17.479
That is all we needed to make a basic NLP tool

00:09:17.479 --> 00:09:18.559
for our purposes.

00:09:19.599 --> 00:09:22.719
So, basically, what this does is that it first determines

00:09:22.719 --> 00:09:25.440
if there's a number present before,

00:09:25.440 --> 00:09:28.320
but also within one of the keyword or phrases,

00:09:28.320 --> 00:09:30.599
and extracts it into its own column.

00:09:30.599 --> 00:09:34.000
And if it recognizes that there's no number present before,

00:09:34.000 --> 00:09:35.760
that's also within the phrase.

00:09:35.760 --> 00:09:37.640
It'll see if there's a number that's afterwards,

00:09:37.640 --> 00:09:39.400
but still within that phrase.

00:09:39.400 --> 00:09:41.039
That was in the keyword data set.

00:09:42.400 --> 00:09:43.840
We then apply this function

00:09:43.840 --> 00:09:46.640
to the entire clinical note data set.

00:09:46.640 --> 00:09:49.799
So, if we apply the results of our NLP,

00:09:49.799 --> 00:09:53.559
natural language processing tool, to our example,

00:09:53.559 --> 00:09:57.400
we can now see that there is a column called billing time

00:09:57.400 --> 00:10:01.320
that has correctly extracted the number of 35 minutes.

00:10:01.320 --> 00:10:03.919
And it knows that none of the other numbers

00:10:03.919 --> 00:10:07.840
in that free text were the billing time.

00:10:09.440 --> 00:10:12.559
So, finally, we then created an outlier variable

00:10:12.559 --> 00:10:15.960
that we can identify potential documentation errors.

00:10:15.960 --> 00:10:18.760
So, at our practice, we found it would be pretty rare

00:10:18.760 --> 00:10:21.799
for a clinician to bill less than 10 minutes of time,

00:10:21.799 --> 00:10:25.359
or more than 100 minutes in a single note.

00:10:25.359 --> 00:10:28.400
So, we use these values as outlier thresholds.

00:10:28.400 --> 00:10:31.679
And then, if the billing time is outside of these thresholds,

00:10:31.679 --> 00:10:33.280
or if it doesn't exist,

00:10:33.280 --> 00:10:36.000
because that is another issue we want to identify,

00:10:36.000 --> 00:10:38.880
if there is no billing information in the note,

00:10:38.880 --> 00:10:40.679
the column is then marked as a one,

00:10:40.679 --> 00:10:44.239
and then zero otherwise, classic binary variable.

00:10:44.239 --> 00:10:46.559
So, this allows our end users, our clinicians,

00:10:46.559 --> 00:10:50.039
to filter the data to identify those outliers quickly.

00:10:51.280 --> 00:10:54.679
So, now a tool is only as good as its validation results.

00:10:54.880 --> 00:10:57.359
And since my background is in epidemiology,

00:10:57.359 --> 00:11:00.440
we, of course, had to conduct a retrospective study

00:11:00.440 --> 00:11:01.559
on all our notes.

00:11:01.559 --> 00:11:03.039
And so, we took all the notes written

00:11:03.039 --> 00:11:07.880
by critical care clinicians in the year 2024.

00:11:07.880 --> 00:11:09.799
So, then we wanted to see if, number one,

00:11:09.799 --> 00:11:11.400
if our tool even worked.

00:11:11.400 --> 00:11:14.039
And number two, if our tool performed better

00:11:14.039 --> 00:11:16.239
than what was our current tool available,

00:11:16.239 --> 00:11:18.119
which was that smart phrase method

00:11:18.119 --> 00:11:19.559
that I had mentioned earlier.

00:11:20.640 --> 00:11:23.320
So, we analyzed a lot of different performance measures

00:11:23.320 --> 00:11:24.280
for our executives,

00:11:24.280 --> 00:11:26.960
but I think the most important one to highlight here

00:11:26.960 --> 00:11:29.520
is the row in the bold at the bottom.

00:11:29.520 --> 00:11:30.760
This is the percentage of notes

00:11:30.760 --> 00:11:33.799
where the billing time was successfully extracted

00:11:33.799 --> 00:11:36.440
or identified as not being there.

00:11:36.440 --> 00:11:40.559
So, our NLP tool, you can see, worked about 93% of notes,

00:11:40.559 --> 00:11:42.280
whereas that smart phrase method,

00:11:42.280 --> 00:11:45.080
it only worked on about 60%.

00:11:45.080 --> 00:11:46.280
And I want to also note

00:11:46.280 --> 00:11:48.200
that these are not small denominators.

00:11:48.200 --> 00:11:52.280
This is almost 285,000 notes,

00:11:52.280 --> 00:11:54.280
written by over 500 clinicians.

00:11:54.280 --> 00:11:56.880
So, you can see how big the impact

00:11:56.880 --> 00:12:00.719
of a functioning natural language processing tool is.

00:12:02.000 --> 00:12:04.359
So, how do we currently use this tool?

00:12:04.359 --> 00:12:07.200
So, following our successful validation,

00:12:07.200 --> 00:12:09.640
for the most part, we still are in the process

00:12:09.640 --> 00:12:13.440
of continuous validation, as I will point out here.

00:12:13.440 --> 00:12:16.840
The tool actually went live in February 2025.

00:12:16.840 --> 00:12:19.919
So, here's our monthly process.

00:12:19.919 --> 00:12:21.919
We first apply the tool

00:12:21.919 --> 00:12:23.919
to the previous month's clinical notes.

00:12:24.799 --> 00:12:26.799
Then the new data is sent

00:12:26.799 --> 00:12:29.919
to critical care leadership for manual review.

00:12:29.919 --> 00:12:32.080
Sometimes they like to look at some certain outliers,

00:12:32.080 --> 00:12:35.000
maybe if a patient is really complex,

00:12:35.000 --> 00:12:37.400
sometimes that justifies a very high billing time,

00:12:37.400 --> 00:12:38.479
and so they just want to make sure

00:12:38.479 --> 00:12:40.719
that everything is up to snuff.

00:12:41.640 --> 00:12:44.440
So, then critical care leadership

00:12:44.440 --> 00:12:47.280
will notify the clinicians if they have notes

00:12:47.280 --> 00:12:49.599
that are within those outliers.

00:12:50.280 --> 00:12:52.080
And if they find that the physician

00:12:52.080 --> 00:12:53.559
hasn't made that many errors,

00:12:53.559 --> 00:12:54.960
or if the errors are pretty minor,

00:12:54.960 --> 00:12:57.520
maybe they put 40 instead of 400,

00:12:57.520 --> 00:12:58.960
or something kind of obvious,

00:13:00.400 --> 00:13:02.200
the clinicians will then be notified

00:13:02.200 --> 00:13:04.400
and the documentations are fixed.

00:13:04.400 --> 00:13:07.960
However, if we find that there's maybe a physician or two

00:13:07.960 --> 00:13:10.640
that is constantly missing documentation,

00:13:10.640 --> 00:13:15.039
or if they're constantly making very inaccurate statements

00:13:15.039 --> 00:13:17.799
all of the time, they then get flagged

00:13:17.799 --> 00:13:19.359
for further investigation.

00:13:20.280 --> 00:13:23.200
And then finally, critical care leadership

00:13:23.200 --> 00:13:25.679
notifies our team if they have found

00:13:25.679 --> 00:13:28.880
any valuable uncaptured phrases

00:13:28.880 --> 00:13:32.320
related to billing text that we can then add

00:13:32.320 --> 00:13:35.640
back to our keyword data set, and the process continues.

00:13:37.200 --> 00:13:39.520
So, the last part I want to talk about

00:13:39.520 --> 00:13:42.799
is our expansions and our future analytics plans.

00:13:42.799 --> 00:13:46.320
So, we want to actually expand this to other specialties.

00:13:46.320 --> 00:13:49.039
Right now, it is only in critical care,

00:13:49.880 --> 00:13:53.559
but we got asked to expand the tool to surgical services

00:13:53.559 --> 00:13:57.159
to use for their operation or procedure notes.

00:13:57.159 --> 00:13:59.960
So, we've been trialing an NLP tool for that instance

00:13:59.960 --> 00:14:02.320
that has had pretty similar success

00:14:02.320 --> 00:14:05.400
as our previous NLP tool.

00:14:05.400 --> 00:14:07.679
And we also like to run some additional analytics

00:14:07.679 --> 00:14:11.359
to see if people are even correcting their notes.

00:14:11.359 --> 00:14:14.320
You know, we create this tool for physicians,

00:14:14.320 --> 00:14:16.119
but we actually want to know if it's being used,

00:14:16.119 --> 00:14:20.479
if it's valuable, if it's just extra manual work for them,

00:14:20.479 --> 00:14:23.239
or if it's going to require some additional education

00:14:23.239 --> 00:14:25.280
or other processes.

00:14:27.280 --> 00:14:29.239
So, in short, our team utilized

00:14:29.239 --> 00:14:31.239
currently available POSIT tools

00:14:31.239 --> 00:14:34.080
to create a natural language processing tool

00:14:34.080 --> 00:14:36.559
that successfully identified billing mistakes

00:14:36.559 --> 00:14:37.919
in clinical notes.

00:14:37.919 --> 00:14:40.239
And we also proved that this tool could be developed

00:14:40.239 --> 00:14:43.400
with readily available and cost-effective tools

00:14:44.320 --> 00:14:46.919
that can be reproducible among organizations

00:14:46.919 --> 00:14:50.799
where access to LLM technology is limited.

00:14:50.799 --> 00:14:52.400
So, now I feel like our clinicians

00:14:52.400 --> 00:14:54.119
don't have to worry so much

00:14:54.119 --> 00:14:56.359
about whether they're making accidental keystrokes

00:14:56.359 --> 00:14:59.239
and whether or not that's going to affect their medical license

00:14:59.239 --> 00:15:01.719
or causing their patients financial harm,

00:15:01.719 --> 00:15:03.919
and they can go back to doing what they do best,

00:15:03.919 --> 00:15:05.960
keeping us safe and healthy.

00:15:05.960 --> 00:15:07.000
Thank you, everyone.

00:15:07.000 --> 00:15:08.599
I'd like to open the floor for questions.

00:15:08.799 --> 00:15:10.200
Thank you, Julianne.

00:15:10.200 --> 00:15:13.200
We have the questions from Slido.

00:15:16.200 --> 00:15:17.200
I'll ask.

00:15:17.200 --> 00:15:22.200
So, this seems from somebody who is medically literate.

00:15:22.200 --> 00:15:25.599
You can either request a BAA from OpenAI

00:15:25.599 --> 00:15:27.599
for HIPAA-compliant LLM calls

00:15:27.599 --> 00:15:31.599
or use a cloud provider like GCP and Azure.

00:15:31.599 --> 00:15:33.599
You can look at the slides and see

00:15:33.599 --> 00:15:36.599
if there's any questions you'd like to ask.

00:15:37.599 --> 00:15:40.599
You can then get a BAA for HIPAA-compliant

00:15:40.599 --> 00:15:41.599
from the cloud provider.

00:15:41.599 --> 00:15:45.599
In fact, cloud providers offer quite a few healthcare offerings

00:15:45.599 --> 00:15:47.599
specifically for this purpose.

00:15:47.599 --> 00:15:50.599
I guess the question is, have you considered this?

00:15:50.599 --> 00:15:52.599
Yes, we definitely have.

00:15:52.599 --> 00:15:55.599
And I'm sure Emory Healthcare is in the process

00:15:55.599 --> 00:15:57.599
of trying to get those things.

00:15:57.599 --> 00:16:00.599
So, we had just switched medical softwares

00:16:00.599 --> 00:16:02.599
within the last two years or so,

00:16:02.599 --> 00:16:04.599
and so we're still trying to learn

00:16:04.599 --> 00:16:07.599
what our medical software capabilities are,

00:16:07.599 --> 00:16:09.599
as well as developing.

00:16:09.599 --> 00:16:12.599
We now have a team called Emory Digital,

00:16:12.599 --> 00:16:14.599
where they're now going to be talking more

00:16:14.599 --> 00:16:16.599
about AI and LLM projects.

00:16:16.599 --> 00:16:18.599
It's all just very, very new.

00:16:18.599 --> 00:16:19.599
So, I'm sure that's in the pipeline,

00:16:19.599 --> 00:16:22.599
but for this time and for the timeliness

00:16:22.599 --> 00:16:24.599
where we had to get this done as soon as possible

00:16:24.599 --> 00:16:27.599
in case a Center for Medicaid and Medicare Service audit

00:16:27.599 --> 00:16:30.599
came around, we had to be a little bit quicker

00:16:30.599 --> 00:16:33.599
and not have to wait for that.

00:16:33.599 --> 00:16:37.599
Thank you so much.

00:16:37.599 --> 00:16:41.599
This one I find interesting myself as well.

00:16:41.599 --> 00:16:43.599
So, what kind of notes or phrases did you see

00:16:43.599 --> 00:16:45.599
causing the errors in the 7%

00:16:45.599 --> 00:16:48.599
that the tool did not identify correctly?

00:16:48.599 --> 00:16:50.599
Yeah, I mean, so some of them range

00:16:50.599 --> 00:16:52.599
from just some misspellings,

00:16:52.599 --> 00:16:55.599
like in adding an extra I to critical,

00:16:55.599 --> 00:16:57.599
which is where the LLM would have been really useful.

00:16:57.599 --> 00:17:01.599
They could have gotten some of those easy misspellings.

00:17:01.599 --> 00:17:06.599
Some of them would just be just time, parentheses,

00:17:06.599 --> 00:17:11.599
15 spaces, and then brackets, smiley face,

00:17:11.599 --> 00:17:17.599
IDK how long I build, maybe 10, question mark.

00:17:17.599 --> 00:17:21.599
So, yeah, we didn't add that line specifically.

00:17:21.599 --> 00:17:23.599
I think we actually went to that physician and went,

00:17:23.599 --> 00:17:25.599
you got to refine it a little bit more,

00:17:25.599 --> 00:17:28.599
but we saw a lot of variation.

00:17:28.599 --> 00:17:32.599
So, the results from that data table were from February,

00:17:32.599 --> 00:17:34.599
and so it's now September.

00:17:34.599 --> 00:17:38.599
We have been adding phrases into that keyword generator

00:17:38.599 --> 00:17:39.599
each time that we've run this,

00:17:39.599 --> 00:17:41.599
and we've gotten to the point now where we've gone,

00:17:41.599 --> 00:17:44.599
well, there are no more that we can really add,

00:17:44.599 --> 00:17:47.599
unless there's those crazy ones that just require

00:17:47.599 --> 00:17:49.599
telling the physician maybe don't document that way,

00:17:49.599 --> 00:17:55.599
but it's now even more refined than that 93%.

00:17:55.599 --> 00:17:56.599
Thank you.

00:17:56.599 --> 00:17:58.599
This is a classic one,

00:17:58.599 --> 00:18:03.599
because this is more of a comment than a question,

00:18:03.599 --> 00:18:05.599
but the person wanted to say that they're very pleased

00:18:05.599 --> 00:18:08.599
to see classic NLP being used rather than the LLMs

00:18:08.599 --> 00:18:09.599
when the LLMs are not necessary,

00:18:09.599 --> 00:18:12.599
so I think that is a hats off for you.

00:18:12.599 --> 00:18:16.599
Yay.

00:18:16.599 --> 00:18:17.599
All right, next question is,

00:18:17.599 --> 00:18:20.599
are there other kinds of data validation you think

00:18:20.599 --> 00:18:23.599
this could be applied to in healthcare billing?

00:18:23.599 --> 00:18:25.599
Oh, tons.

00:18:25.599 --> 00:18:27.599
I think one of the other side projects

00:18:27.599 --> 00:18:28.599
that our team is working on

00:18:28.599 --> 00:18:30.599
is that there's actually different subsets of billing.

00:18:30.599 --> 00:18:32.599
You can bill for critical care,

00:18:32.599 --> 00:18:34.599
or you can bill for what's just called

00:18:34.599 --> 00:18:35.599
evaluation and management,

00:18:35.599 --> 00:18:38.599
so basically if you are seeing a patient

00:18:38.599 --> 00:18:40.599
who is super, super sick,

00:18:40.599 --> 00:18:43.599
you get reimbursed more by Center for Medicaid and Medicare

00:18:43.599 --> 00:18:45.599
versus if you're just seeing a patient

00:18:45.599 --> 00:18:47.599
just for routine or for physicals,

00:18:47.599 --> 00:18:50.599
you get paid a different way,

00:18:50.599 --> 00:18:53.599
and so we've actually been refining the NLP tool

00:18:53.599 --> 00:18:55.599
to actually say,

00:18:55.599 --> 00:18:57.599
is this critical care billing

00:18:57.599 --> 00:18:59.599
or is this non-critical care billing

00:18:59.599 --> 00:19:00.599
so that we can really make sure

00:19:00.599 --> 00:19:02.599
if you're an ICU physician,

00:19:02.599 --> 00:19:03.599
you're billing for critical,

00:19:03.599 --> 00:19:06.599
and that if you are a primary care doctor,

00:19:06.599 --> 00:19:08.599
you are not billing for critical care

00:19:08.599 --> 00:19:11.599
because that is also a legality issue,

00:19:11.599 --> 00:19:14.599
so yeah, tons of expansions we have planned.

00:19:14.599 --> 00:19:16.599
All right, Julianne, thank you so much.

00:19:16.599 --> 00:19:17.599
Thank you.

00:19:17.599 --> 00:19:18.599
Thank you.

00:19:18.599 --> 00:19:21.599
Thank you.

